05090nam a22007815i 9780231548670DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018048962  a97802315486707 a10.7312/edmo190022doi  a(DE-B1597)526807  a(OCoLC)1104227736  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1083.T42bE36 2019 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a809.1/032231 aEdmond, Jacob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMake It the Same :bPoetry in the Age of Global Media /cJacob Edmond. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b34 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterature Now00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. POSTCOLONIAL MEDIA -- t2. THE ART OF SAMIZDAT -- t3. MAKING WAVES IN WORLD LITERATURE -- t4. SHIBBOLETH -- t5. COPY RIGHTS -- t6. CHINESE ROOMS -- tRECAPITULATIONS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOur world is full of copies. This proliferation includes not just the copying that occurs online and the cultural copying of globalization but the works of avant-garde writers challenging cultural and political authority. In Make It the Same, Jacob Edmond examines the turn toward repetition in poetry, using the explosion of copying to offer a deeply inventive account of modern and contemporary literature.Make It the Same explores how poetry—an art form associated with the singular, inimitable utterance—is increasingly made from other texts through sampling, appropriation, translation, remediation, performance, and other forms of repetition, as opposed to privileging “innovative” or “original” works. Edmond tracks the rise of copy poetry across media from the tape recorder to the computer and through various cultures, languages, and places, reading across aesthetic, linguistic, geopolitical, and media divides. He illuminates the common form that unites a diverse range of writers from dub poets to conceptualists, samizdat wordsmiths to Twitter-trolling provocateurs, analyzing the works of such writers as Kamau Brathwaite, Dmitri Prigov, Caroline Bergvall, Vanessa Place, Christian Bök, Hsia Yü, and Tan Lin. Edmond develops an alternative account of modernist and contemporary literature as defined not by innovation—as in Ezra Pound’s slogan “make it new”—but by a system of continuous copying. Make It the Same transforms global literary history, showing how the old hierarchies of original and derivative, center and periphery are overturned when we recognize copying as the engine of literary change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCopying processes. 0aDigital media. 0aLiterature and technology. 0aPoetry, ModernxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz978311061036908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/edmo1900240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231548670423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231548670.jpg  a978-3-11-061036-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a9